Predict Students' Dropout and Academic Success

Introduction

The dataset contains information from multiple higher education institutions about students from various fields and nationalities. The goal is to classify the students into 3 strongly imbalanced categories which describe their academic performance: droput, enrolled, and graduated.

Source of the data: 10.24432/C5MC89 (alternate URL).

def println(*args, **kwargs):
    print(*args, **kwargs)
    print("")


def pprintln(title, *args, **kwargs):
    print(f"{title}:")
    kwargs.setdefault("indent", 2)
    pprint.pp(*args, **kwargs)
    print("")


plot_layout = (1, 1)
next_subplot = 0


def plt_layout(rows, cols, figsize):
    global plot_layout, next_subplot
    plot_layout = (rows, cols)
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=rows, ncols=cols, figsize=figsize)
    fig.tight_layout()
    next_subplot = 0


def plt_next(title):
    global plot_layout, next_subplot
    next_subplot += 1
    ax = plt.subplot(plot_layout[0], plot_layout[1], next_subplot)
    plt.title(title)

    return ax


def plt_hist(title, *args, **kwargs):
    plt_next(title)
    plt.hist(*args, **kwargs)


def plt_scatter(t1, t2, d1, d2, *args, **kwargs):
    ax = plt_next(f"{t1} vs. {t2}")
    ax.set_xlabel(t1)
    ax.set_ylabel(t2)
    plt.scatter(d1, d2, *args, **kwargs)


def plt_show():
    plt.show()
    next_subplot = 0


def invert_dict(dct):
    return dict((value, idx) for idx, value in dct.items())


def assign_numbers(data, col):
    mapping = invert_dict(dict(enumerate(sorted(data[col].unique()))))

    print(f"Renumbering {str(col)!r}")
    
    for k, v in sorted(((kk, vv) for kk, vv in mapping.items()), key=lambda x: x[0]):
        print(f"  {k:>10} --> {v}")

    return data[col].apply(lambda v: mapping[v])

Histograms

In[74]:
cols = 3
rows = len(data.columns)
target_vals = data["Target"].unique()
plt_layout(rows, cols, (12, rows * 3))

data_grouped = {
    tv: data[data["Target"] == tv] for tv in target_vals
}

for col in data.columns:
    if col == "Target":
        continue
        
    bins = (
        20 if str(data.dtypes[col]) != "int64" else len(data[col].unique())
    )
    range_ = (data[col].min(), data[col].max())

    for tv in target_vals:
        plt_next(f"{col} {tv} vs. all")
        plt.hist(data[col], bins=bins, label="all", range=range_)
        plt.hist(data_grouped[tv][col], bins=bins, label=tv, range=range_)
        plt.legend()

plt_hist("Target", data["Target"], bins=len(target_vals))

Linear correlations

In[76]:
# Make the target numeric
data["Target_num"] = assign_numbers(data, "Target")

# Reorder features in order to bring the target column closer to the labels
cols = ["Target_num"] + [col for col in data.columns if not col.startswith("Target")]

plt_layout(1, 1, (12, 8))
corr = data[cols].corr()
sns.heatmap(corr, cmap="BrBG", annot=False)
plt.show()
